To solve this problem, we need to increment the integer represented by the array digits by 1. This problem resembles adding 1 to a number with potential "carry" propagation. Hereâ€™s how we can approach it:

Start from the Last Digit: Begin from the last element in the array, which represents the least significant digit.
Increment and Handle Carry: Add 1 to this digit. If it becomes 10, set it to 0 (because it needs a carry), and move to the next most significant digit.
Continue the Carry: Repeat the process as long as thereâ€™s a carry to propagate.
Final Carry: If thereâ€™s still a carry after processing all digits (like going from [9, 9, 9] to [1, 0, 0, 0]), we need to add an additional 1 at the beginning of the array.
Solution Code
javascript
Copy code
function plusOne(digits) {
    for (let i = digits.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        if (digits[i] < 9) {
            digits[i] += 1;
            return digits;
        }
        digits[i] = 0;
    }
    // If we exited the loop, we had a carry all the way through
    digits.unshift(1);
    return digits;
}
Explanation of the Code
Loop from the End: We start from the last element in the array and move backward.
Incrementing and Checking for Carry:
If the current digit is less than 9, we increment it and return the array immediately because thereâ€™s no carry.
If itâ€™s 9, we set it to 0 (which indicates a carry needs to move to the next digit).
Handle the Edge Case for All 9s:
If we complete the loop and every digit was a 9, weâ€™ll end up with an array of 0s (e.g., [9, 9] becomes [0, 0]).
In this case, we insert 1 at the beginning, making the result [1, 0, 0].
Examples
Example 1
javascript
Copy code
plusOne([1, 2, 3]); // Output: [1, 2, 4]
Example 2
javascript
Copy code
plusOne([9, 9, 9]); // Output: [1, 0, 0, 0]
